  "prompt": "How can you determine the derivative of [math]\\sin x^2[/math]?",
  "response": "To find the derivative of \\( \\sin(x^2) \\), we use the chain rule from calculus. The chain rule states that if you have a composite function \\( f(g(x)) \\), the derivative is given by:\n\n\\[\n(f(g(x)))' = f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)\n\\]\n\nIn this case, let \\( u = x^2 \\), so that our function becomes \\( \\sin(u) \\). First, we'll find the derivative of \\( \\sin(u) \\) with respect to \\( u \\), which is \\( \\cos(u) \\). Then, we'll find the derivative of \\( u = x^2 \\) with respect to \\( x \\), which is \\( 2x \\).\n\nNow, applying the chain rule:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x^2) = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx}(x^2)\n\\]\n\n\\[\n= \\cos(x^2) \\cdot 2x\n\\]\n\nThus, the derivative of \\( \\sin(x^2) \\) is:\n\n\\[\n2x \\cos(x^2)\n\\]",
